Queues : A queue is a data structure that can hold many elements.

Think of a queue as people standing in line in a supermarket.
The first person to stand in line is also the first who can pay and leave the supermarket. 
This way of organizing elements is called FIFO: First In First Out.
======================≈=============================================================================

Basic operations we can do on a queue are:

Enqueue: Adds a new element to the queue.
Dequeue: Removes and returns the first (front) element from the queue.
Peek: Returns the first element in the queue.
isEmpty: Checks if the queue is empty.
Size: Finds the number of elements in the queue.

========================================================================================================

import java.util.Queue;
import java.util.LinkedList;

public class QueueExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Creating a Queue using LinkedList
        Queue<String> queue = new LinkedList<>();

        // 1. Adding elements to the queue
        queue.add("First Person"); // Throws exception if capacity is full
        queue.offer("Second Person"); // Returns false if capacity is full
        queue.add("Third Person");
        System.out.println("Current Queue: " + queue);

        // 2. Examining the head element
        String head = queue.peek(); // Returns null if empty
        System.out.println("Head of Queue (peek): " + head);
        head = queue.element(); // Throws exception if empty
        System.out.println("Head of Queue (element): " + head);

        // 3. Removing elements from the queue
        String removedPerson = queue.poll(); // Returns null if empty
        System.out.println("Removed with poll(): " + removedPerson);
        System.out.println("Queue after one removal: " + queue);

        removedPerson = queue.remove(); // Throws exception if empty
        System.out.println("Removed with remove(): " + removedPerson);
        System.out.println("Queue after second removal: " + queue);
        
        // 4. Checking size and emptiness
        System.out.println("Queue size: " + queue.size());
        System.out.println("Is queue empty? " + queue.isEmpty());

        // 5. Clearing the queue
        queue.clear();
        System.out.println("Queue after clearing: " + queue);
        System.out.println("Is queue empty? " + queue.isEmpty());
    }
}


Output of the code:
Current Queue: [First Person, Second Person, Third Person]
Head of Queue (peek): First Person
Head of Queue (element): First Person
Removed with poll(): First Person
Queue after one removal: [Second Person, Third Person]
Removed with remove(): Second Person
Queue after second removal: [Third Person]
Queue size: 1
Is queue empty? false
Queue after clearing: []
Is queue empty? true


